                    <msContents>
                        <summary>The first of two volumes of an incomplete, illustrated <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_2149">Shāhnāmah</title>
                            (Book of Kings), by <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Abū al-Qāsim Manṣūr Firdawsī (fl. ca. 940–1020)</persName>, together with <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_26578"><idno>Persian MS 978</idno></ref>, apparently created as a large single manuscript, but then later divided into two by a former owner. 
                            The poet Abū Manṣūr Daqīqī (d. 975) commenced a thousand
                            lines, but after his death, Firdawsī completed the work shortly  
                            before the year <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1000">1000 CE</date>. He
                            drew upon a number of pre-Islamic Pahlavi middle Persian sources,
                            principally the now-lost <title>Khwadāynāmag</title> (Book of Lords)
                            that recounted the ancient rulers of Persian until the Sassanian period,
                            as well as Iranian mythology and folklore. This volume opens with an introduction and illuminated carpet pages, and also contains seven paintings, with many blank spaces intended for illustrations left incomplete.
                            The colophon, which appears at the end of the second volume, describes how <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" role="scr">Shihāb Kātib</persName> (Shihāb the scribe) completed this manuscript on behalf of <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" role="pat">Mīrzā Abū al-Qāsim Bayg</persName>, after Friday prayers on <date>15 Muḥarram 1006 AH (28 August 1597 CE)</date>, possibly in <placeName cert="medium" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002148" key="place_7002148">Shiraz</placeName>, therefore the earliest securely-dated manuscript of this work held in the Rylands.</summary>
